'''Charles George Johnson''' (1886{{endash}}14 October 1950) was a chemist, businessman and political figure in [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]].
==Biography== Johnson was born in [[Essex]], England in 1886 and led an adventurous life, including a spell of [[boxing]] professionally, before arriving in Adelaide in 1925.<ref name=obit>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article45658933 Death of City Councillor], ''The Advertiser'', Monday 16 October 1950, p.4. Accessed 30 January 2011</ref> He first came to public notice as an [[Australian Labor Party (South Australian Branch)|Labor Party]] (ALP) candidate for a North Adelaide seat in South Australia's House of Assembly in 1933.
In August 1934, Johnson founded the cleaning products company [[Jasol Chemical Products]]. "Jasol" was an [[acronym]] for "Johnson's Antiseptic Soluble Oils Limited." Early deliveries were done by Johnson on a [[pushbike]].
In 1945, when he was well known for his association with the Jasol firm, Johnson was elected as Councillor on the [[Adelaide City Council]]. He resigned from the ALP in 1947.<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article43747401 Councillor resigns from A.L.P.], ''The Advertiser'', 11 December 1947, p.3. Accessed 30 January 2011</ref> He consistently voted against generosity towards retiring councillors, mayors and employees, even when he acknowledged that the person had served the council exceptionally well.<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article30508961 Points from Letters], ''The Advertiser'', Friday 24 January 1947, p.12. Accessed 30 January 2011</ref><ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article43749418 Salary rise for Town Clerk], ''The Advertiser'', 23 December 1947, p.2. Accessed 30 January 2011</ref> He resigned in 1949 to stand as an alderman but was defeated.
He was vice-president of the Adelaide sub-branch of the [[Returned and Services League of Australia|Returned Sailors Soldiers and Airmens Imperial League of Australia]].<ref name=obit/>
Johnson lived on [[South Terrace, Adelaide]]. He died in the [[Repatriation General Hospital, Daw Park]] in 1950. He was survived by his wife Millie Johnson.<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article45658804 Births Deaths and Marriages], ''The Advertiser'', 16 October 1950, p.16. Accessed 30 January 2011</ref>
